Security.

Security is the pillar about protecting data and identities against credible threats, and it has a set of non-negotiables.

For identity, use roles, not users, for everything, put permission boundaries on developer roles, and federate through single sign-on rather than local users. Practice least privilege, reviewing analyzer findings and sizing policies to actual usage. Encrypt data, using customer-managed keys for sensitive data, default encryption on storage and volumes, and secure transport everywhere. Keep secrets in a secrets manager with rotation, never in plain text in code, images, or environment variables. Apply network controls: private subnets for compute, public ones only where strictly needed, deny-by-default security groups, private endpoints for AWS services, and a firewall on internet-facing endpoints. Turn on detection everywhere, threat detection across the organization, a central findings hub, and sensitive-data discovery on data stores. And keep an audit trail to locked storage with continuous configuration recording and periodic access reviews.

The customer side of the shared responsibility model, your data and your identities, is always yours; AWS protects the rest.
